      "content": "To achieve a deep, dark crust, you'll want to focus on increasing the temperature and controlling the moisture levels in the dough. Adding more sugar to the dough can actually hinder the Maillard reaction, as it can lead to a more rapid caramelization and a less complex flavor profile.\n\nInstead, try increasing the oven temperature to around 425°F (220°C) or even higher, but keep a close eye on the bread to avoid burning. You can also try using a broiler for a few minutes to get a more intense, caramelized crust.\n\nTo maintain the internal texture, make sure to not over-proof the dough, and consider using a steam injection or a hot water bath to create a more even, crispy crust. A steamy environment can help to create a more intense Maillard reaction, while also helping to retain moisture in the dough.\n\nIt's also worth noting that some bakers use a process called \"oven spring,\" where they preheat the oven to a very high temperature (around 500°F or 260°C) for a short period of time, then reduce the temperature to achieve a more even, golden-brown crust. This technique can help to create a more intense Maillard reaction, but it requires careful temperature control",
